#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;qemu-system-x86_64 [...] -drive file=/dev/hdb,media=disk"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:511
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"A host drive used by a &vmguest; must not be accessed concurrently by the "
"&vmhost; or another &vmguest;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:517
#, no-c-format
msgid "Freeing Unused Guest Disk Space"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:518
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"A <xref linkend=\"gloss.vt.storage.sparse\"/> is a type of disk image file "
"that grows in size as the user adds data to it, taking up only as much disk "
"space as is stored in it. For example, if you copy 1 GB of data inside the "
"sparse disk image, its size grows by 1 GB. If you then delete for example "
"500 MB of the data, the image size does not by default decrease as expected."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:526
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"That is why the <option>discard=on</option> option is introduced on the "
"&kvm; command line. It tells the hypervisor to automatically free the "
"<quote>holes</quote> after deleting data from the sparse guest image. Note "
"that this option is valid only for the <literal>if=scsi</literal> drive "
"interface:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:533
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.sudo;qemu-system-x86_64 [...] -drive file=/path/to/file.img,if=scsi,"
"discard=on"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:535
#, no-c-format
msgid "Support Status"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:536
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<option>if=scsi</option> is not supported. This interface does not map to "
"<emphasis>virtio-scsi</emphasis> , but rather to the <emphasis>lsi SCSI "
"adapter</emphasis> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:544
#, no-c-format
msgid "IOThreads"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:545
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"IOThreads are dedicated event loop threads for virtio devices to perform I/O "
"requests in order to improve scalability, especially on an SMP &vmhost; with "
"SMP &vmguest;s using many disk devices. Instead of using &qemu;'s main event "
"loop for I/O processing, IOThreads allow spreading I/O work across multiple "
"CPUs and can improve latency when properly configured."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:553
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"IOThreads are enabled by defining IOThread objects. virtio devices can then "
"use the objects for their I/0 event loops. Many virtio devices can use a "
"single IOThread object, or virtio devices and IOThread objects can be "
"configured in a 1:1 mapping. The following example creates a single IOThread "
"with ID <literal>iothread0</literal> which is then used as the event loop "
"for two virtio-blk devices."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:561
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.user;qemu-system-x86_64 [...] -object iothread,id=iothread0\\\n"
"-drive if=none,id=drive0,cache=none,aio=native,\\\n"
"format=raw,file=filename -device virtio-blk-pci,drive=drive0,scsi=off,\\\n"
"iothread=iothread0 -drive if=none,id=drive1,cache=none,aio=native,\\\n"
"format=raw,file=filename -device virtio-blk-pci,drive=drive1,scsi=off,\\\n"
"iothread=iothread0 [...]"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:567
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The following qemu command line example illustrates a 1:1 virtio device to "
"IOThread mapping:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:571
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.user;qemu-system-x86_64 [...] -object iothread,id=iothread0\\\n"
"-object iothread,id=iothread1 -drive if=none,id=drive0,cache=none,aio=native,"
"\\\n"
"format=raw,file=filename -device virtio-blk-pci,drive=drive0,scsi=off,\\\n"
"iothread=iothread0 -drive if=none,id=drive1,cache=none,aio=native,\\\n"
"format=raw,file=filename -device virtio-blk-pci,drive=drive1,scsi=off,\\\n"
"    iothread=iothread1 [...]"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:579
#, no-c-format
msgid "Bio-Based I/O Path for virtio-blk"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:580
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For better performance of I/O-intensive applications, a new I/O path was "
"introduced for the virtio-blk interface in kernel version 3.7. This bio-"
"based block device driver skips the I/O scheduler, and thus shortens the I/O "
"path in guest and has lower latency. It is especially useful for high-speed "
"storage devices, such as SSD disks."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:587
#, no-c-format
msgid "The driver is disabled by default. To use it, do the following:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:592
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Append <option>virtio_blk.use_bio=1</option> to the kernel command line on "
"the guest. You can do so via <menuchoice><guimenu>&yast;</"
"guimenu><guimenu>System</guimenu><guimenu>Boot Loader</guimenu></"
"menuchoice> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:598
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"You can do it also by editing <filename>/etc/default/grub</filename> , "
"searching for the line that contains <option>GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX_DEFAULT=</"
"option> , and adding the kernel parameter at the end. Then run "
"<command>grub2-mkconfig &gt;/boot/grub2/grub.cfg</command> to update the "
"grub2 boot menu."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:607
#, no-c-format
msgid "Reboot the guest with the new kernel command line active."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:613
#, no-c-format
msgid "Bio-Based Driver on Slow Devices"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:614
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The bio-based virtio-blk driver does not help on slow devices such as spin "
"hard disks. The reason is that the benefit of scheduling is larger than what "
"the shortened bio path offers. Do not use the bio-based driver on slow "
"devices."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:623
#, no-c-format
msgid "Accessing iSCSI Resources Directly"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:625
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"QEMU now integrates with <literal>libiscsi</literal> . This allows QEMU to "
"access iSCSI resources directly and use them as virtual machine block "
"devices. This feature does not require any host iSCSI initiator "
"configuration, as is needed for a libvirt iSCSI target based storage pool "
"setup. Instead it directly connects guest storage interfaces to an iSCSI "
"target LUN by means of the user space library libiscsi. iSCSI-based disk "
"devices can also be specified in the libvirt XML configuration."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:639
#, no-c-format
msgid "RAW Image Format"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:640
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This feature is only available using the RAW image format, as the iSCSI "
"protocol has some technical limitations."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:655
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The following is the QEMU command line interface for iSCSI connectivity."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:660
#, no-c-format
msgid "virt-manager Limitation"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:661
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The use of libiscsi based storage provisioning is not yet exposed by the "
"virt-manager interface, but instead it would be configured by directly "
"editing the guest xml. This new way of accessing iSCSI based storage is to "
"be done at the command line."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:669
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.sudo;qemu-system-x86_64 -machine accel=kvm \\\n"
"  -drive file=iscsi://192.168.100.1:3260/iqn.2016-08.com.example:314605ab-"
"a88e-49af-b4eb-664808a3443b/0,\\\n"
"  format=raw,if=none,id=mydrive,cache=none \\\n"
"  -device ide-hd,bus=ide.0,unit=0,drive=mydrive ..."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:673
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Here is an example snippet of guest domain xml which uses the protocolbased "
"iSCSI:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:678
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<![CDATA[<devices>\n"
"...\n"
"  <disk type='network' device='disk'>\n"
"    <driver name='qemu' type='raw'/>\n"
"    <source protocol='iscsi' name='iqn.2013-07.com.example:iscsi-nopool/2'>\n"
"      <host name='example.com' port='3260'/>\n"
"    </source>\n"
"    <auth username='myuser'>\n"
"      <secret type='iscsi' usage='libvirtiscsi'/>\n"
"    </auth>\n"
"    <target dev='vda' bus='virtio'/>\n"
"  </disk>\n"
"</devices>]]>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:692
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Contrast that with an example which uses the host based iSCSI initiator "
"which virt-manager sets up:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:696
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<![CDATA[<devices>\n"
"...\n"
"  <disk type='block' device='disk'>\n"
"    <driver name='qemu' type='raw' cache='none' io='native'/>\n"
"    <source dev='/dev/disk/by-path/scsi-0:0:0:0'/>\n"
"    <target dev='hda' bus='ide'/>\n"
"    <address type='drive' controller='0' bus='0' target='0' unit='0'/>\n"
"  </disk>\n"
"  <controller type='ide' index='0'>\n"
"    <address type='pci' domain='0x0000' bus='0x00' slot='0x01'\n"
"             function='0x1'/>\n"
"  </controller>\n"
"</devices>]]>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:711
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using RADOS Block Devices with &qemu;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: qemu_running_vms_qemukvm.xml:712
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"RADOS Block Devices (RBD) store data in a Ceph cluster. They allow "
"snapshotting, replication, and data consistency. You can use an RBD from "
"your &kvm;-managed &vmguest;s similarly to how you use other block devices."
